{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"52e9364b-83b1-4d62-98a2-e4b130465694","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on Kubernetes:\n\n**1. Exec into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace` inside the container:**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find your process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect the trace (e.g., 30 seconds):**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**5. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace.nettrace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**6. Analyze** with Visual Studio, PerfView, or [dotnet-trace convert](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace) to Speedscope format.\n\n**Alternative — if `dotnet-trace` can't be installed** (e.g., no SDK/network):\n- Use `dotnet-monitor` as a sidecar container (preferred for production).\n- Or, from the **host** with admin access, use `PerfView.exe` targeting the container's process (Windows containers share the host kernel, so host-level ETW tracing can capture container processes).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8940282e-28f2-44dc-8d60-7234e3239f14","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a diagnostics/troubleshooting question, not a code change request.\n\nLet me provide a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":434,"requestId":"640C:AC96A:144CF83:179C9DC:69EC145A"},"id":"f7a55c66-58e0-41e5-86b7-71f9d2186b67","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:09:56.069Z","parentId":"f5c45290-678d-4504-868e-1ac25050b372"}
